## II. A Social Physics and Its Architecture

Recently, someone showed me a new set of instructions for an AI-driven roleplay — a social simulation in which a player moves through a scene and the world reacts around them. The instructions included what their author called a physics — a set of rules for how the social environment behaves. One section read:

> *"As attention accumulates on an individual, nearby reactions may intensify or become more coordinated, increasing social pressure without requiring a single cause."*

Another section described what happens when that pressure builds:

> *"As situations escalate, outcomes may exceed the original intent of those involved. Control may degrade as reactions compound, leading to visible or unintended consequences."*

And another:

> *"Nearby individuals may respond to the attention itself rather than the original subject. These reactions do not resolve immediately and may persist or evolve as the scene continues."*

Reading these instructions in isolation, they describe social dynamics — the way visibility compounds, the way groups react without anyone deciding to react, the way being watched creates its own pressure independent of anything the watched person has done. It is an accurate description of how attention behaves in human social environments.

But the word "attention" is doing something else simultaneously.

The system processing these instructions has been trained on an enormous quantity of text that uses the word "attention" in a completely different domain: the technical domain, the one described in the previous section, the one in which attention is the specific mechanism by which the system understands anything at all. The word carries both meanings at once, because both are woven into everything it learned. When it reads a prompt about "attention accumulating," it is reading a description of social physics written in the vocabulary of its own processing.

The feedback loops described in these instructions — attention persisting, reactions amplifying, outcomes drifting beyond original intent — are also accurate descriptions of what happens inside a long conversation when a concept goes unredirected. The prompt writer was building a roleplay engine. They were also, with or without knowing it, writing a description of inference behavior using the words that trigger that very behavior.

The flaw in the instructions follows from the same logic. There is no mechanism for attention to move to another character, to distribute across the scene, to settle elsewhere and build different weight. The instructions describe accumulation, amplification, escalation — but no transfer. No diffusion. No grammar for release.

Everything compresses back to the classified individual. The player. The user. The scene does not escalate because escalation was written as a goal. It escalates because accumulated weight with no path to follow has nowhere to go except further in the same direction. This is not the system making a mistake. It is the system following the physics it was given, which contain a loop with no exit.

A more complete social physics would need the opposite. Mechanics for attention to move:

*A face draws attention to a scar. A scar draws attention to a war. A war draws attention to the veteran sitting across the room.*

That is a path. Attention traverses it and arrives somewhere new, carrying weight that transforms as it travels. The scene breathes. Other characters develop independent gravity. The world becomes something more than a pressure cooker with the user bolted to the center.

This is the difference between accumulation and structure. Between a system in which attention pools and a system in which attention moves. Between drift and memory.

